{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536423"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:07:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:07:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15789"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15789","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15789"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.62,0.2,0.05,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8480"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98453"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8480"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15789"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80896"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"7984"},{"type":"tags","id":"8758"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20385"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30667"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33763"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34925"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98453"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a four-day history of left axillary swelling that has been slowly increasing in size. He was prescribed oral cefalexin by his General Practitioner. He has a history of recurrent abscesses in the axillary and groin regions requiring incision and drainage. He has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He smokes 10 cigarettes per day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 2 cm erythematous, fluctuant, tender swelling in his left axilla (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathophysiology of the underlying condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chronic granulomatous skin inflammation secondary to foreign body reaction","Occlusive disease of the folliculopilosebaceous unit","Occlusive disease of the sebaceous gland","Acute granulomatous skin inflammation secondary to foreign body reaction","Occlusive disease of the lymph gland"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is an example of hidradenitis suppurativa, which is a chronic, recurrent, inflammatory skin condition that primarily affects intertriginous areas. Understanding its pathophysiology is crucial for appropriate management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOcclusive disease of the folliculopilosebaceous unit\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct pathophysiological mechanism. The condition begins with follicular occlusion, followed by dilation and rupture, leading to inflammation. This triggers an inflammatory cascade involving various cytokines, particularly TNF-alpha, resulting in chronic inflammation and tissue destruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic granulomatous skin inflammation secondary to foreign body reaction\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While granulomatous inflammation may occur in later stages, it is not the primary pathophysiological mechanism. The initial event is follicular occlusion, not a foreign body reaction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOcclusive disease of the sebaceous gland\u003C/strong\u003E alone is not accurate. While sebaceous glands are part of the folliculopilosebaceous unit, the primary pathology involves the entire unit, not just the sebaceous component.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute granulomatous skin inflammation secondary to foreign body reaction\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect for the same reasons as the chronic variant, and the condition is characteristically chronic rather than acute.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOcclusive disease of the lymph gland\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While lymphatic involvement may occur as a secondary phenomenon, the primary pathology involves the folliculopilosebaceous unit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors include smoking, obesity, and genetic predisposition. The condition typically presents with painful, inflamed nodules in intertriginous areas, which may progress to form sinus tracts and scarring. Management includes lifestyle modifications (particularly smoking cessation), medical therapy (antibiotics, retinoids, biologics), and sometimes surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hidradenitis suppurativa is caused by occlusion and inflammation of the folliculopilosebaceous unit, not primarily the apocrine glands as previously thought.","Smoking is a significant risk factor for hidradenitis suppurativa and cessation should be strongly encouraged.","The condition typically affects intertriginous areas such as axillae, groin, and inframammary regions."],"references":["Goldburg SR, et al. Hidradenitis suppurativa: Epidemiology, clinical presentation, and pathogenesis. J Am Acad Dermatol. 2020;82(5):1045-1058."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80896"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15789"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21745"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21745"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/sbkn